'''Homa Nategh''' (1935 &ndash; 1 January 2016)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiozamaneh.com/253955 |title=هما ناطق، تاریخ‌نگار و استاد دانشگاه، درگذشت |website=Radiozamaneh.com |date= |accessdate=2016-01-03}}</ref> was an Iranian [[historian]], Professor of History at [[Tehran University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ted.lib.harvard.edu/ted/deliver/~iohp/Nategh,+Homa.06 |title=Nategh, Homa. .; Harvard Iranian Oral History Project; Harvard Center for Middle Eastern Studies; Harvard University |website=Ted.lib.harvard.edu |date=1984-04-07 |accessdate=2016-01-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Women in Iran: Gender politics in the Islamic republic |last=Shahidian |first=Hammed |page=35 |year=2002 |publisher=[[Greenwood Publishing Group]] |isbn=978-0-313-31476-6 }}</ref> A specialist in the contemporary [[history of Iran]], she resided in [[Paris]], France until her death.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/pages/remembering-homa-nategh|title=Remembering Homa Nategh – Encyclopaedia Iranica|last=electricpulp.com|website=www.iranicaonline.org|language=en|access-date=2017-12-27}}</ref> She was active during [[Iranian Revolution|Iran's 1979 revolution]]. After the revolution she was purged from the [[University of Tehran main entrance|University of Tehran]] and moved to [[Paris]], where she was appointed as professor of the Iranian Studies at the [[Sorbonne University|Sorbonne]]. In Sorbonne she published several articles on Iranian history in [[Qajar dynasty|Qajar period]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Touraj Atabaki & Nasser Mohajer|first=|date=11 Apr 2016|title=OBITUARY - In Memoriam Homa Nategh (1934-2016)|url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/00210862.2016.1142256?scroll=top&needAccess=true|journal=Journal Iranian Studies|volume=49|pages=325–326|via=}}</ref>
